EPA Chief Scott Pruitt on postponing planned Obama administration emissions reduction directives
After 15 states were sued by the Environmental Protection Agency, its boss, Scott Pruitt, rescinded his earlier decision to delay implementation of the former Obama administration's plan to reduce carbon dioxide emissions.
Pruitt introduced changes as part of his plan. It thus responds more briskly than previous governments to the needs of state environmental regulators.
However, he did not mention a legal challenge filed against his previous position in a federal appeals court.
This concerns the last deadline, which was set for 1 October, when states should start complying with the 2015 regulation to reduce ground-level ozone.
Pruitt announced in June that he would postpone the agreement for one year and order a more detailed study of the plan to avoid "interference with local decisions or impending economic growth."
Pruitt, who served as Oklahoma's attorney general before president Donald Trump took over as EPA chief, has long served as a staunch opponent of stricter environmental regulations.
Since settling in Washington, Pruitt has repeatedly shifted or delayed regulations proposed by the chemical and fossil fuel industries.
Wednesday's abrupt reversal is the biggest legal setback for Pruitt's regulatory agenda.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that an EPA executive overstepped his authority in an effort to detract from the Obama administration's plan to require oil and gas companies to reduce methane leaks.
In a statement released Wednesday night, Pruitt proposed his version of ozone standards and strengthened the EPA's commitment to working with states through complex processes and meeting new standards within a given timeframe.
"Under the previous administration, the EPA often failed to meet deadlines and waited to be sued by activist groups and others, agreeing to settle and further set plans," said Pruitt, who filed more than a dozen lawsuits against the EPA in his previous position.
"We do not believe in regulation through litigation and take compliance seriously.
We never joke about our status and the authority that comes out of it."
However, the EPA statement states that Pruitt can use "the possibility of delay and all other legally available authorities" at some point to ensure that regulations "are based on sound policies and the most accessible information."
Congressional Republicans are pushing for a more comprehensive rewrite of ozone rules.
The White House budget approved last month seeks to delay implementation of the 2015 rules by at least eight years.
The measure still hasn't passed the Senate.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who headed the coalition of states that sued the EPA this week, said the group has no legal authority.
"The reversal of EPA opinion - following our lawsuits - is an important victory for the health and safety of the 6.7 million New Yorkers and more than 115 million Americans directly affected by air pollution," Schneiderman added.
New York was joined by California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont, Washington and Washington, D.C.
Ground-level ozone is produced when common harmful substances emitted by cars, power plants, oil refineries, chemical power plants and other sources react in the atmosphere with solar radiation.
The resulting smog can cause serious respiratory problems in sensitive people and thousands of premature deaths each year.
Public health advocates and environmentalists are grateful for Pruitt's sudden change.
"It's disturbing what pressure needs to be exerted to change the minds of those responsible and protect the air we breathe," said Lori Ann Burd of the Center for Biological Diversity.
"We must continue to struggle with the Trump administration's ideological campaign to help polluters and special interests."
