This is due, among other things, to the fact that, for all its global aspirations, China does not welcome foreigners with open arms, christopher balding, an economics professor at Peking University, assesses the situation in the world's most populous country in an article for Bloomberg.
An example that speaks for itself is China's visa policy.
Only 13 countries have visa-free travel with China, and citizens of the others must obtain a visa in advance.
At Chinese offices in the US, therefore, the crowds are comparable to chinese New Year celebrations.
A visa costs $140, but if you don't want to wait long hours in line for it, you have to pay $100 or more for additional services.
Such restrictions create significant economic barriers.
A study by the Journal of Economics and Finance showed that the need for a visa reduces the number of visitors to a country by 70 percent.
In 2015, only two million Americans visited mainland China, while 1.8 million Americans visited Hong Kong, which accounts for less than 3% of China's gross domestic product and is home to less than 1 percent of the population.
China often exacerbates the problem itself by using tourism to achieve its political goals, such as disputes with Taiwan and South Korea.
When China restricted traffic to South Korea in the spring as part of a spat over South Korea's anti-missile system, The South Koreans retaliated and avoided China.
In May, the number of visits fell by 42 percent year-on-year, while Japan recorded an 85 percent increase.
All this affects macroeconomic stability.
According to a recently published report by the US Central Bank, the Fed may have abandoned China as much as $190 billion as a result of Chinese foreign travel, while China receives about $35 billion a year in selling currency to incoming tourists.
According to official balance of payments figures, China had a deficit of $217 billion in tourism last year, equivalent to 44 percent of China's entire surplus in trade in goods.
So a small number of tourists are dealt a very painful blow to a country that is anxiously preventing capital outflows.
However, the above factors are only one manifestation of more general reticence towards foreigners.
In many places in China, virtually no one has heard of immigrants.
As of 2013, there were fewer than a million foreigners living across China.
Some individual cities have more in the United States.
Even Japan, which is not exactly a crossroads of immigration, has double that.
At the same time, a number of scientific papers show that immigrants tend to revive economic growth, entrepreneurship, and innovation.
However, you will hardly find them in China.
Solving these problems will be politically challenging, but the step on offer is to simplify the visa system.
Other Asian countries, not only India and Vietnam, have recently made great efforts to simplify and make visa procedures easier and cheaper.
If China wants more foreign tourists and their hard currency, it should be easier for them to get there.
