Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV drug given before sex to reduce the risk of HIV disease.
Tests have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV transmission among at-risk patients.
The application of PrEP before sex means that there are enough specific drugs in the patient's body to prevent infection.
These drugs can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
The patients tested include gay or bisexual men, transgender people and people with HIV-positive partners who are not successfully treated.
Clinics will identify eligible participants who sign consent to participate in testing, including men, women, transgender people, and individuals with a partner whose HIV status is not yet controlled by appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with a GP in the UK can also apply to their local sexual health clinic and apply for potential participation in testing.
The programme will cost taxpayers £10 million and NHS England signed a contract this week to distribute drugs after winning an international public contract.
The trial period is designed to gather clinical evidence and assess prep's full potential, its targeting, use and implementation on a large scale.
Simon Stevens added: 'This important intervention should complement and fully nur the ever-expanding and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
It's another milestone in more than 30 years of trying to stop one of the greatest challenges to human health.'
Deborah Gold, executive director of the National Aids Trust (NAT), said: 'We are witnessing a decisive moment in the fight against HIV.
If PrEP is administered correctly and patients are at risk, it will offer the possibility of transforming England's HIV epidemic.
From September, NSH will offer patients at high risk of HIV infection a powerful new tool that is individually controlled and not subject to the need to persuade a partner, leading to an improvement in the quality of many lives.
