Lavender from Provence threatens climate change
Lavender has become a symbol of Provence in the south-eastern French region, but is now threatened by climate change.
Lavender is declining due to dry climate and harmful insects, causing consternation on the faces of researchers and farmers looking for solutions.
Eric Chaisse, an expert at crieppam agricultural research institute in Provence, said: "Lavender cultivation in Provence is at risk because in the last few years this plant has been exposed to climate change, which brings with it less precipitation in spring and autumn.
This affects the lifespan of lavender.
Cicades and grasshoppers carrying micro-bacteria that thrive in a dry climate are also to blame."
The stakes are high.
Lavender attracts tourists, and the oil produced from them is an important component of perfumes and cosmetics.
Eric Chaisse said: "Instead of long and beautiful flowers grow smaller, under-developmental and often weak plants.
The amount of oil obtained from these lavenders is, of course, smaller."
A possible solution may be to distribute water more efficiently and slow down the evaporation of water from the soil, but also to spray lavender with a protective mixture of clay and water, and to breed more species resistant to dry weather.
