Dinosaurs used camouflage to avoid enemies
At first glance, it looks like a statue, however terrifying.
Researchers have now uncovered the conclusions of the first findings of an amazing creature the size of a rhinoceros whose perfectly preserved remains - which experts have called the 'Mona Lisa of dinosaurs' - were found by a Canadian miner.
The remains were preserved to such a high degree that experts were able to determine the reddish-brown color of its scaly skin and said the dinosaur had a 'troubled past'.
An article in the journal Current Biology stated that it is 'the best preserved armored dinosaur ever found and one of the best dinosaur species in the world'.
The fossil is a new species of the family Nodosauridae. The dinosaur lived in the Cretaceous period, about 110 to 112 million years ago.
His perfectly preserved condition literally shocked the researchers, who described it as 'truly remarkable'.
According to National Geographic, the armored white-eater is still the best-left fossil of its kind.
Shawn Funk, who discovered the fossil on March 21, 2011 while drilling at the Suncor Millenium mine near Alberta, Canada, is behind the find.
He came across what appeared to be an alien object and decided to explore it more closely.
The fossil was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
Researchers spent the next six years working to uncover the animal from a huge piece of land weighing 1,100 kg.
After finishing the work, the dinosaur is ready to be discovered.
'All you have to do is turn a little blind eye and you'll believe he's asleep,' said head of work Caleb Brown and naturalist at the Royal Tyrrell Museum, where the animal is on display.
'It will certainly go down in history as one of the most beautiful and well-to-do dinosaur species - the Mona Lisa dinosaurs.'
By studying his skin, researchers found that this herbivore - despite being covered in armor and resembling a walking tank - was most likely facing a serious threat from carnivorous dinosaurs.
The heavily armored dinosaur used red and white camouflage to protect against predators and used a camouflage system used by many of today's animals.
Experts say this has allowed him to better blend in with his surroundings and avoid enemies. The cloaking system suggests it was a favorite food of larger dinosaurs.
News of the 110 million-year-old dinosaur of the Nodosauridae family first appeared in the paper in May. It is currently available for viewing at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
The researchers named him Borealopelta markmitchelli after museum technician Mark Mitchell, who along with the team spent more than 7,000 hours carefully uncovering the fossil.
Thanks to the amazingly well-to-do state of the fossil, Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists documented the patterns and shape of scales and armor all over the body.
They revealed the method of camouflage commonly used by today's animals in defense - the upper part of the animal was darker than its lower part.
Although this masking effect is common in nature, the researchers' findings are surprising because Borealopelta's size far exceeds today's animals using the same technique.
So it is possible that the dinosaur was so many predators that evolution preferred camouflage to confrontation in survival.
Many contemporary animals with camouflage - for example, deer, zebra or armadillo - are much smaller and also more vulnerable as prey, suggesting that the nosodaurus literally had to fight for its survive.
'The predation of the huge and heavily armored dinosaur illustrates the danger posed by predators during the Cretaceous period,' Brown said.
Chemical analysis of the organic components contained in the scales also revealed that the dinosaur skin was probably reddish-brown in color.
Researchers continue to study the animal and search for other findings about its life, including preserved stomach contents, to track down its last meal.
They believe the dinosaur fell into the river after death and was carried to the sea, where it sank to the bottom.
The Alberta region had the same climate at the time as florida today, and rivers and oceans stretched much further inland than they do today.
'This nodosaurus is truly remarkable in that it is completely covered in perfectly preserved scaly skin and at the same time preserved in three dimensions so that we can see its original size,' Brown said.
'For these reasons, the animal looks practically the same as it did in the Cretaceous period.
You don't have to use your imagination to reconstruct it; just turn a little smy-eyed and it looks like he's just sleeping.'
In the Cretaceous period, giant theropods, carnivorous dinosaurs, walked the Earth on two legs.
Although the king of all dinosaurs - tyrannosaurus rex - lived several million years after Borealopelta, this armored dinosaur may have been a favorite prey of his equally fearsome ancestors.
These include Acrocanthosaurus, an 11.5-meter-long monster weighing over 6 tons.
The researchers, whose latest findings were published in the journal Current Biology, believe borealopelt's body was washed out to sea after being mummified in mud.
Shawn Funk, who discovered the fossil on March 21, 2011 while drilling at a Suncor Millenium mine near Alberta, Canada, is behind the find.
According to the museum, it is the best-living armored dinosaur in the world, including leather and armor, which is also complete from mule to hip.
The animal reached an average length of 5 meters and weighed up to 1300 kg.
Two 50 cm barbs protruded from his shoulders.
Researchers believe this herbivore sailed through what is now Canada until it ended up in the river that washed it into the sea.
His underwater tomb preserved the body in perfect condition.
Fossil remains of this species are also preserved to the extent that the armored plates around the skull still cover the remains of the skin.
As Michael Greshko wrote for National Geographic, 'finding such a well-heeled individual can be compared to winning the lottery.
The longer I follow him, the more shocking the find seems to me.
