How did one activist learn the answer to the question: 'Whose Streets?'
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell shook her body.
The day after she arrived in New York, the St. Louis native sat down on her bed in an Airbnb room and went through Facebook posts on her phone.
In doing so, she came across a contribution from a high school student.
"Police have just shot and killed an 18-year-old boy whose body is still lying in the street," it read.
She was surprised that no one else had written this post to her, so she shut down Facebook and opened Twitter.
User @TheePharoah constantly retweeted her posts on the wall.
The St. Louis rapper posted on Twitter about the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed 18-year-old who was shot and killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
He posted a photo of Brown's body lying limp on the street, from where he was not taken after four hours.
"That's crazy," Ferrell thought.
But death was nothing new for her and her community.
She put down her phone to go back to him the night she watched tweets about people gathering on Canfield Drive.
She was watching photos of police tapes and people screaming. One of the men claimed to be the victim's father, holding a sign that said "Ferguson P.D. killed my unarmed son"!
She watched the live news - one of the policemen standing in front of a group of protesters, holding a leash and a barking dog at the other end.
In another video, another officer, she said, was holding a gun that he pointed at the crowd, shouting, "I'm going to kill you all... animals.'
"That's not normal," Ferrell told her.
"This isn't the kind of murder we're used to and we can call normal.
I felt goose bumps all over my body.
"I was angry and crying."
She immediately booked a return flight and went home the next day.
After landing at 11:00 p.m., she picked up her 6-year-old daughter from her father and decided to go to Ferguson in the morning.
The story of what happened to Ferrell and the city of Ferguson over the next three years is described in the new documentary "Whose Streets?", which will be released in theaters August 11.
It is a story of survival and protest, love and resistance, strength and unymingness told from the point of view of people living in the community who take to the streets and demand answers.
On her way to Ferguson, Ferrell began a dialogue with her daughter - dressed in a floral jersey and the same floral headband - on a topic they had discussed many times before - "the experience of black people."
"Remember when I taught you about how black people had to fight for what they believed in?" she recalls of the interview.
"We're going to Ferguson right now because the police killed an 18-year-old, and that's not right."
"There was no way I didn't take her with me," Ferrell said later.
"Today's events are the culmination...of events that have occurred in the past.
She must have known and seen it with her own eyes and grown into it.
She needed to develop not only in activism and organizing, but she also had to know the difference between different layers of black experience and what we had to do to free us.
Even though I'm able to provide her with conditions in which she doesn't experience racism firsthand, she's no different from any other black child-woman.
I feel that if I could protect her from this experience, I would only harm her."
Upon arrival in Ferguson, the first stop was South Florissant Road opposite the police department, which became a base for activists who expected officer Darren Wilson's words about his possible involvement in the incident.
This is where Ferrell and her daughter met a local businessman who prepared food for others.
Together they prepared food in bags and helped deliver it to protestants.
In Ferrell's eyes, a new type of activism was slowly being born.
"My activism was turned upside down after August 9," Ferrell said, adding that while studying at the University of Missouri-St. Louis was president of the Minority Student Nurses Assn. and sought to introduce health care and food in black communities.
"I had no experience with the organization.
It was natural."
A few weeks later, during an evening demonstration, Ferrell met the later co-director of the documentary, Sabaah Folayan.
Folayan said he and her cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Farrar wanted to "just document" ongoing events.
Ferrell, however, thought, "Are you working on a documentary or are you trying to find a story that can be used?"
This type of skepticism perceived into the community through many people, often white people, who wanted to capitalize on pain and determination.
As Folayan explained in an interview: "We have heard that the voices of people born and raised in Ferguson are very often neglected, and we wanted to change that."
Folayan has already established a collaboration with co-author Damon Davis, a respected local artist who deals with the subject of death row inmates.
Ferrell and six other locals who were followed by the "Whose Streets?" team in the years following Brown's assassination also participated in the project.
"No one speaks for us in this document, but it's our statement," Davis said.
"That was important to me - how these people will be represented - because I will be represented in the same way."
While the documentary was not aimed at focusing on Ferrell's experience - in an effort to show that the movement "is not about the savior leader, but about community rapprochement," Folayan said - it turned out that she was the most open to participating in filming.
The documentary "Whose Streets?" thus describes a very personal aspect of Ferrell's life, such as how she fell in love with her wife.
"I felt naked," Ferrell said with a smile on her face at the thought of the first moment she watched the final version of the documentary.
"But I understood that in order to do this job and humanize black people, I had to open up."
In addition, Ferrell's story highlights the role of an eccentric black woman in a broader aspect of the Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the movement's three founders - who created a #BlackLivesMatter campaign in response to the 2012 killing of teenager Trayvon Martin on social media - call themselves weirdoes.
"Black eccentric women in leadership positions are ultimately behind maintaining the movement," Ferrell said, "because we're constantly fighting on multiple fronts.
Black eccentric women must bear the weight of these events."
Folayan agrees with this statement, adding that "the movement is actually supported by black women and a large number of eccentric black women."
However, she insists that "this is not just an affirmative action" and Ferrell is not the main heroine of the documentary because of her views.
"She was the driving force and power source," she said.
"that she is the one on the front lines is no accident, because life at these crossroads in the skin of a black weirdo woman is dangerous.
You can feel the energy in front of the screen."
Meanwhile, back in Ferguson, television cameras have cleared their positions, but heavy racial ties between the community and the police remain.
Ferrell is serving two-and-a-half years probation for blocking the highway during demonstrations.
She described the social political atmosphere in what she calls home as "Disorder."
Yet she continues the effort she's committed to since she took to the streets of Ferguson three years ago.
"It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It's our duty to win.
We must love and support each other.
All we have to lose are our chains."
