A Becoming Resemblance: artist creates portraits using Chelsea Manning's DNA
In the center of one of the rooms of New York's Fridman Gallery are several faces of different skin tones - white, black and brown - suspended from the ceiling on wires. Each one of them looked like the last one fell out of their eyes.
All 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from mouth swab and hair swab sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent her samples from Fort Leavenworth Prison, where the former analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for unauthorized wikileaks disclosure of classified cables.
The new exhibition, which opened on August 2, is called A Becoming Resemblance.
It is the result of two years of correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, who combines her experience in technology, computer science and the arts, and Manning - a transgender and pioneering dissident whose sentence was reduced by Obama three days before he left the post of US President.
By algorithmically analyzing Manning's DNA and using 30 portraits to illustrate what a person with this genotype would look like, Dewey-Hagborg created a sharp, if not intellectual, commentary on dna's malleability - as well as the many ways DNA can be interpreted - and the inherent determinism of these interpretations, as well as identity.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward Manning, spoke from a young age about her being considered a woman. She was convicted in 2013 on 20 charges, including violation of six espionage laws, computer fraud and theft.
All her photographs were being held by prison staff. Only one lower-quality black-and-white photo has been leaked, in which Manning, visibly concerned, sits in the driver's seat in the platinum blond wig she is now associated with.
In 2015, there were still positive reactions to Dewey-Hagborg's 2012 stranger visions project.
As part of this project, Dewey-Hagborg used various forensic items - such as cigarette butts and chewing gum - to create an image of the possible forms of these people.
And it was at this time that she received an email from Paper Magazine.
"They were doing an interview with Chelsea Manning in prison, and they wanted to supplement the article with a portrait," Dewey-Hagborg explained at the opening of the new exhibition.
However, visitors and photography were not allowed, so they turned to Chelsea to ask if she would be interested in a DNA portrait.
The artist and her imprisoned muse became friends within two years through correspondence.
They even created a comic book called Suppressed Images, illustrated by Shoili Kanung, which presented a vision of what would happen if Chelsea were pardoned and could attend the exhibition in person.
Indeed, a few days after the comic was published, President Obama requested Manning's release, a welcome change after several unbearable years in a Kansas military prison.
Interestingly enough, the exhibition is taking place at a time when Donald Trump is waging war on people seeking to disclose government information and transgender soldiers as he tries to find new ways to incite resentment in areas he should support with his tweets.
In response to a question about this special timing, Dewey-Hagborg stated that "everything happens for a reason."
Under the artist's statement on one of the gallery walls, Manning calls out with her huge signature (the letter "i" in her last name is doped with her heart) at the end of "self-factionalism based on gender, race, sexuality, and culture."
On the opposite side are sequences of her mitochondrial DNA - a centipede of the letters C, G and A recorded with a pencil.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, according to the artist's sophisticated scientific dictionary), Dewey-Hagborg wanted to illustrate how surprisingly similar, at least biologically, we all are.
"I hope that people will take away from this, that our genome doesn't care who we are, and that genetic data is subjective and everyone can interpret it their own way," Dewey-Hagborg said. Her 2007 work Spurious Memories on video is also on display.
"DNA tells many different stories, this is 30 of them."
The last specimen of the exhibition, located in a separate room, is a single page from the above graphic novel.
It depicts Manning emergeing king kong-like from united states disiplinary barracks with a megaphone in her hand.
"Once they stop you from speaking, they win," it says.
"Never be silenced."
"It's a direct transcript from one of the letters," the Philadelphia artist said.
"When I think about it, I get goose bumps."
Manning has not yet personally visited the exhibition - as predicted in the comics - but when she does, she will be greeted in the center of the room with her masks, her own genomic effits, lined up like a crowd of Protestants.
This was also the purpose of the exhibition, including the nearly 160 cm tall statue of Maning, on which her genetic haplogroups are recorded with a pencil.
"They've been placed on walls in the past, but this time I wanted them to radiate the feeling of a crowd," Dewey-Hagborg said of the portraits.
"I wanted to create the impression of a mass movement that takes the form of Chelsea and frees her."
