Startups to help your company not become the next Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure employee satisfaction at her e-commerce startup, but she couldn't find the appropriate survey.
The answers were often inaccurate, unhelpful, or even deceptive.
And despite promising anonymity for the survey, some employees expressed their distrust of the process.
"I was looking for consistency and objectivity," said Errett, owner of San Francisco-based hair care company Madison Reed, which employs 75 people.
So she asked for outside help.
New human resources start-ups are constantly emerging on the market to help companies with employee satisfaction surveys.
By creating and licensing software with a specific intent to measure employees' obligations, startups allow companies to make quick votes, target specific teams and demographic groups, offer complete employee anonymity, and a complaints hotline, and in some cases also allow whistleblowers to bypass supervisors and contact directors directly.
"There are tools like Strava and Fitbit on the market that track your health, but where's Fitbit for your company?" said Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of Reedwood City-based startup Glint.
Errett said that Dglint has made her more aware of what her employees think and feel in three years.
In addition to quick surveys and team-specific votes, Glint offers a company temperature map and a cursory overview of the groups with the highest number of complaints, as well as an overview of low-rated managers - allowing the user to work on the remedy.
Companies are beginning to realize the need to pay attention to the culture of the work environment - in case they become the next Uber - which is teasing in scandal after a former employee posted on his blog describing the corporate environment and harassing employees who dare to speak out.
For start-ups like Glint, the demand for corporate culture surveys is a lucrative business opportunity.
According to Let's Talk Payments, a website that looks at technical and financial progress, the value of the global control, regulation, and compliance industry could exceed $118.8 billion by 2020.
Startup Convercent, of Denver, Colorado, which helps companies prevent and detect inappropriate behavior, saw a small increase in interest and activity at the beginning of the year, just before the Uber scandals.
Convercent's nearly 600 clients include Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Recently, Uber has also taken over its wings.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send customizable "flash" surveys, collect confidential information in real time, and view temperature maps of problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous text hotline that allows employees to report inappropriate behavior.
Where the Director-General is involved in the problem, complaints shall be sent directly to the Management Board.
"The Court of Public Opinion has empowered regulators," said Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of convercent, a startup.
If a company is convicted of mistreatment of its employees or unethical behavior - and if regulators do not act - it may face costly consequences as a result of customer boycotts, employee exhaustion, or lawsuits, Quinlan added.
The Ruby Tuesday restaurant network, which employs more than 25,000 people across 500 locations, has been using Convercent for more than a year to raise employees' awareness of corporate policies and procedures and provide an easy way to contact corporate executives.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report any problem, they had to find a phone number or email to the company's management, officially file a complaint, and hope for a good resolution.
It was often a deterrent and unpleasant experience, said James Vitrano, Ruby Tuesday's general counsel, who said there had not been a reliable way to track employee complaints before.
Now that the company is using Convercent, it ensures that problems that have never been reached before by managers sitting in offices are ensured to be miles away from actually dealing with complaints - such as discrimination, harassment, or unfair treatment.
"It's close to a holistic, overall view of employee experience," said Vitrano, who runs Ruby Tuesday's risk management group.
"At the same time, we protect shareholders from lawsuits by employees."
Companies stopped taking ethics, values, and employee participation lightly in 2002 after accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed following enron's collapse over abuses of employee ethics, Quinlan said.
But it wasn't until "social media lit up the whole thing" that companies began to realize that in the online world they couldn't simply hide their skeletons in a closet.
"Before people started using technology to track ethics, they relied on faith," Quinlan added.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software in the form of a service for which companies pay regular fees.
It is a business model and an opportunity endorsed by bold capital investors who have supported both start-ups.
Convercent raised a total of $10 million from companies like Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital as part of its February campaign, eventually taking $47 million in capital.
Glint raised $10 million from Bessemer Venture Partners in November and raised $60 million throughout the campaign.
These investments are hardly surprising given the mutual nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
The growing number of researches clearly confirms that today's employees expect more from their workplace than ever before.
And in competitive markets such as Silicon Valley, high salaries and interesting projects are not the main advantage.
Employees want to perceive that they are accepted and appreciated and that they devote their time to a company that strives for a positive mission.
"If people are happy at their jobs, they feel that their voice is being heard, and that their work is rewarding, they are striving for the success of the company," said Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefits and benefits at LinkedIn, which uses both Convercent and Glint.
Investors make money when a company is doing well and companies are thriving if its employees are satisfied.
And when an analytical tool appears on the market to ensure employee engagement and commitment to the company, it's no wonder there are plenty of investors who will support that effort.
According to work culture experts, it is important to have data on employee satisfaction.
But the data itself is pointless if the company does not take the necessary steps.
The fact is that once a company requests feedback from its employees, big changes can occur.
And if the change does not happen quickly - at worst at all - it can provoke disappointment and lack of interest in employees.
"Once you ask for 4,000 opinions, you have to be prepared for 4,000 conversations," said Russell Raath, director of consulting at Kotter International, who has witnessed many companies relying too much on the data itself.
"Because once you've finished things, the employees start asking themselves, 'Did they hear me at all?
Are they interested in me?
And if not, then why should I care?'" "
Madison Reed, which now conducts monthly employee surveys, can solve the problem within a day thanks to Glint, Errett said.
After collecting feedback from employees frustrated by slow decision-making and communication quality, Errett was able to reorganize several teams within the company and start communication training to solve the problem.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining a very important view of its employees and hopes to achieve high employment in the long run in an industry known for frequent layoffs.
"If you don't work to create a transparent work environment, employees won't trust you," Vitrano added.
"And once you start losing employees, you lose customers.
And with the outflow of customers, the whole company goes bankrupt."
