Making a graphic novel: the story of A Castle in England
The small Scotney Castle recently starred in squeeze's music video, and Margaret Thatcher also found refuge there during the 1970s and 1980s.
Scotney, however, witnessed 700 years of turbulent history from his cosy place by the River Bewl in Kent, England, which inspired the curly-haired Jamie Rhodes of YorkShire - known for his penchant for historical documentations - to create a graphic novel.
"The sight of a man who is 300 years dead fascinates me," rhodes says with a straight face.
"When I hold a letter in my hands, I feel a personal connection."
The graphic novel A Castle in England documents the lives of families who lived at Scotney Castle from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian period. Each story is illustrated by a different British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
But it's not Rhodes' first book inspired by archives: he's also the author of Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories (2014), a collection inspired by British Library documents - a project that was very emotional for him.
"I was intrigued by the thumbprint on a letter written by a double agent in the 1970s who worked for the Jakobits," he said.
"That's his thumbprint!
And letters always smell like smoke, because in those days you had to light a candle to read.
When I smell the letter now, 300 years later, it's like I'm going back in time.
How I love archives!"
For someone so fascinated by old papers, the support from the National Trust and Arts Council England and the possibility of staying in the castle for almost four months is almost like a dream. ("To tell you the truth, I've extended my stay a little.")
Rhodes spent time exploring the Victorian "new" castle, browsing the archives and studying many treasures and curiosities, such as the head of a hyena on the wall and bottles that had been dumped in a ditch for centuries.
He walked around the grounds exploring the ruins of the old castle, talking to gamekeepers, gardeners and occasionally artists who worked on illustrations for his book.
At night, he "drank whiskey and wrote."
Scotney's confidential history is relatively unknown, as the National Trust only gained access to documents in 2006 following the death of its last heir, Elizabeth Hussey.
When Rhodes arrived at the site 10 years later, employees were only just beginning to infiltrate the archives, which Rhodes described as "aristocrats of many centuries throwing their hands around saying, 'Take it to the attic'."
Diaries, letters from the British Empire, maps depicting property: "You may think a land dispute is boring," Rhodes said, "but I came across one case where two families were tussling over birch.
Stop it, people!"
Some of the stories in the book use the castle as a springboard and delve deeper into English history, including a story called The Labourer, which follows a man who leaves a newly built castle to join the English Uprising of 1381.
"I found a record of a musing on the castle in 1380, which was called knightly families of Kent and Sussex in the book," Rhodes said.
"The English uprising actually began in this area, and I thought rebellion was a good starting point.
Maybe they're connected after all."
Other stories are firmly linked to the history of the castle - for example, The Priest, which tells the story of a Jesuit priest who was hidden by darrell's family for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler, about an 18th-century smuggler named Arthur Darrell, who allegedly staged his own funeral when he filled the coffin with stones (which was only discovered a few years after the coffin was uncovered).
Rhodes' favorite family is the Darrells: "I was intrigued by the male generation - men of the time were always in debt and spent money on things they couldn't afford.
Different generations of the Darrell family dealt with this by marrying rich or old ladies - I imagine they were handsome gentlemen who liked to be behead heiresses."
With the end of his stay at the castle, Rhodes is looking for more adventures.
He recently returned from a two-week stit in the Finnish wilderness, where he soaked inspiration for his next book on Elämänmäki, a former sanatorium from the early 20th century that was engulfed in nature.
But it is a special place for Scotney.
"I was sad when I left," he said.
"I thought, 'Now I'm going to get the hell back to real life'."
