Patients are usually reminded not to use meat and dairy products to alleviate symptoms. However, researchers at the University of Washington found that the essential amino acid tryptophan contained in the protein helps to create immune cells that promote bowel resistance.
Study leader Dr Marco Colonna explained that immune cells protect the intestines and ensure the degradation of harmful microbes from food.
The number of inflammatory cells is balanced by the number of cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging sensitive tissue.
As soon as the scales tilt to the side of inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease may occur.
As part of the research, scientists found the presence of immune cells promoting body tolerance in the stomach of mice with a specific bacteria.
This bacterium requires the presence of Tryptophan - one of the building blocks of proteins - to form cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We have found a link between one type of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is a common part of the gut microbiome and the development of cells that promote body tolerance.
The more tryptophan mice had in their diet, the more these immune cells."
At the same time, he suggested that if the same proves true for humans, then the combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet would help develop a more tolerable and less inflammatory intestinal environment.
In a study of a kind of immune cells that promote body tolerance, postgraduate researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas discovered that one group of test mice had these cells, while the other group of the same mice kept separately lacked cells.
She inferred that one group of mice had a different gut microbiome - a community of bacteria, viruses and fungs that commonly dwell in the gastrointestinal tract.
The intestines of mice were tested using the DNA sorting method, and researchers found six types of bacteria in mice with immune cells that were missing from a second group of mice.
Mice that were brought up in a sterile environment and lacked an intestinal microbiome - so they did not develop this kind of immune cells - were given the L. reuteri bacteria - and developed immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grown L. reuteri in fluid and then transferred small amounts of fluid - without the bacteria - to under-development immune cells that were kept in isolation.
Immune cells have evolved into tolerant cells.
After removing the active ingredient from the fluid, it turned out to be a byproduct of tryptophan metabolism known as indolyl-3-acetic acid.
When researchers doubled the amount of Tryptophan in the diet of mice, the amount of these cells increased by 50 percent. At the same time, the number of cells decreased by half after half the doses of Tryptophan were halved.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerant cells as mice, and most of us store L. reuteri bacteria in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether tryptophan by-products from L. reuteri cause cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but defects in tryptophan-related genes have been detected in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
Dr Cervantes-Barragan added: "Each of us should probably strive to develop these cells because they control the inflammation of the inner surface of the intestines.
Potentially high levels of Tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri may increase the cell population.'
