White House prop cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
The White House's decision to fly a Navy helicopter to the South Lawn to celebrate the U.S. manufacturing industry last month came at $24,000, according to Navy records released by TIME.
The green-and-white Sikorsky VH-3D helicopter, also called Marine One in the presence of the president on board, was the highlight of a July 17 program at the White House that showcased U.S. design programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and several senior White House officials surveyed product shows from all 50 states.
A helicopter from Connecticut was displayed next to a Maine yacht, a Wisconsin fire truck and a forklift from Mississippi.
A White House military officer issued a fragmentary order, or FRAGO, and requested the helicopter's presence less than 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn as part of an "emergency," marine helicopter squadron one (HMX-1) - the unit in charge of helicopter management - said.
"I wanted to make sure you were aware of such an important event," hmx-1 commander wrote in an email to his superior, the Navy's deputy commander for aviation the day before the event began.
The report indicated that the helicopter would arrive on the South Lawn at approximately 7:00 a.m. on July 17 for the parade, which is scheduled to begin at 3 p.m. and will remain in place until the entire site, which was scheduled to be completely evacuated between 6 p.m. and 9 p.m.
The email also said that if there is a delay in leaving the White House, a replacement crew will be sent for the return flight due to working time regulations.
The original crew remained at the scene that evening along with the helicopter, along with a unit of security personnel.
The footage - obtained by TIME Weekly - did not show whether a second crew was eventually dispatched.
The Hatch Act prevents state officials from using government property for political purposes.
Records indicate that HMX-1 is investigating a possible violation of this regulation.
"We wondered if it was a violation of the Hatch Act and were assured that everything was in order," the commander wrote.
"Sounds like you've been blocked," the deputy commander wrote back.
This "Made in America" parade was designated an official event by the White House, and the Hatch Act would not apply to it.
But even official events have political overtones.
As he attended the event, the president pushed for health reform, which passed the Senate, and spoke of trying to rein in government regulations.
The use of air vehicles such as Marine One or Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents use them when traveling.
However, their presence purely for presentation reasons is unusual.
Trump ordered a check in February after the president's plane was flying in the background at his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida. His Twitter account is flooded with complaints about his predecessor's use of the presidential plane.
"The White House is pleased with the 'Made in America' parade, which showcased products from all 50 states that Americans make from American materials," said Deputy Press Secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 helicopter crews often train to land in the Washington area and on the South Lawn, rehearsing possible arrivals with the President of the United States at the White House with maximum accuracy.
While Trump was attending the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 made 58 training landings at the White House.
The flight to the Made in America parade was part of the current crew training, a state official said.
On the same day, a helicopter unit flew another 11 hours as part of "non-resident support missions."
The White House said no other props were covered by taxpayers' money.
A Sikorsky spokesman said the company had no involvement in the helicopter's display negotiations on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep budget records for presidential flights, and the exact cost of the parade is difficult to determine, according to the Navy.
According to the Department of Defense, the hourly price for fiscal year 2017, DoD reimbursements for VH-3D expenses are $24,380 per flight hour.
Unit records show a time of 30 minutes from marine corps air facility quantico in Virginia and back.
The White House argues that the actual operating costs of the helicopter are well below that amount.
"It's very misleading to list taxpayers' expenses based on estimates of reimbursements," Walters said.
"These estimates include personnel, maintenance and many other hidden costs that are included in the annual costs."
According to a 2015 RAND study, reimbursements of DoD expenses do not include personnel costs, but include fuel price, maintenance, and contract costs.
Then-White House Press Secretary Sean Spicer defended the use of the helicopter for the parade.
"The idea of this week's show is to introduce products made in the U.S.," Spicer said.
"I am aware that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to the defense of our state, and that they provide work to hundreds, if not thousands, of people.
I think, like most Americans, that we are proud of the helicopter and other military installations that countless American citizens are involved in making.
This is a fact to be recalled."
It's unclear if Trump was on his way to the South Lawn to see the helicopter. The only thing that can be said for sure is that he got behind the wheel of one of the fire trucks.
Back at the White House, Trump addressed a Sikorsky representative and joked with the media about his own fleet of products.
"I know Sikorsky very well," the president said, "I own three myself."
